rmk: As well as drumming and (at the end of the clip) a flight call from a Great Spotted Woodpecker, other species are nicely recorded in the sequence.  Here is the list: GREAT SPOTTED WOODPECKER drums seven times. Note how the resonance of some drums change, especially the final two - because the bird moves to a different piece of tree trunk. The woodpecker can also be heard tapping [0:57] and then it flies a short distance, giving its rather manic 'roving' call as it does so [1:33]. CHIFFCHAFF sings at 0:07, 0:16, 0:23.  CHAFFINCH sings at 0:28, 0:37 and a few more times. WILLOW WARBLER sings at 0:31 and 1:02. LONG-TAILED TIT calls from 0:44 until the 55th second. BLACKCAP sings at 0:57, 1:05, 1:11, 1:16, 1:26 and 1:31. DUNNOCK sings at 1:20.  Also in the background - Wren, Moorhen (one call) and Woodpigeon.
